Correct me if i am wrong, which i probably am. But i highly doubt that all solids etc would just 'turn to dust' or 'cease' to exist'.

If all oxygen molecules disappeared, concrete based things like buildings etc would definitely turn to dust since oxygen is basically a binding agent in it. Definitely not in just a vacuum though.

Not too sure about furniture or clothing, but my guess is that all non metals would turn to dust as well, since they have oxygen in their molecular structure as well.

But most metals don't turn into dust, they just weld together, right? 'Cold welding' is what it's called. And to my understanding most (if not all) metals are not composed with any oxygen in their molecular structure. So even if literally all oxygen molecules disappeared, metals should still stay solid?

There are also other non solid things that don't contain any oxygen as well. Hydrochloric acid being one example. But that is irrelevant to this since I am talking about solids. I would appreciate a list/link to a list of all things which do not contain oxygen though.

The images of people suffocating are slightly misleading. No one would actually experience suffocation because the feeling of suffocation is not triggered by a lack of oxygen, but rather, a build up of CO2. When breathing an inert atmosphere (without oxygen, the air is almost completely nitrogen), gas exchange in the lungs still takes place, so there is no feeling of suffocation. However, because your body is deprived of oxygen, you would collapse within a few seconds.

Cars in motion powered by internal combustion engines wouldn't stop immediately. Too much inertia is involved. If the engine stops while the car is in motion, it will remain spinning, even if the car has an automatic. It will slow down, but it would take far longer than five seconds to stop in nost cases. Once atmospheric oxygen returned the engine would start back up so long as it was still rotating. Cars of the last 25 years coast with the engine off but spinning in some situations anyway - if you take your foot off the gas, and the car is still moving fast enough to keep everything turning, the car's fuel injection stops feeding fuel until a certain RPM threshold is reached.

0:32 that's definitely true, an engine would besically stop running. However, if a car is moving, then there'd be no major effect. The engine would stop outputting energy, but it would remain connected to the wheels. The kinetic energy of the vehicle would continue moving the engine and all accessories. The engine would still generate a vacuum, so you'd have power brakes. It would also still generate electricity, so no problem there. It would also still generate hydraulic pressure if the car has hydraulic steering, so it'd feel normal too.

It'd feel like taking your foot off the accelerator. In fact, under normal operation, doing this will cause the engine computer to completely cut off fuel to the engine to save fuel when coasting.
